WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:09.210
SPEAKER 1: And I'm very excited
to welcome our guests here

00:00:09.210 --> 00:00:09.710
today.

00:00:09.710 --> 00:00:11.930
This is really awesome.

00:00:11.930 --> 00:00:16.129
Quick intros-- so
we're chatting today

00:00:16.129 --> 00:00:22.670
about "Nancy," which is WNYC
Studios' LGBTQ-themed podcast

00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:24.890
about how we define ourselves
and the journey that we

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:26.510
take to get there.

00:00:26.510 --> 00:00:30.680
And my guests are
Tobin Low and Kathy Tu.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:33.764
And prior to "Nancy,"
Tobin was a producer--

00:00:33.764 --> 00:00:35.180
I'm going to just
read this out so

00:00:35.180 --> 00:00:38.280
that, you know, I don't
mess it up, because I will.

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:39.920
Prior to "Nancy,"
Tobin was a producer

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:42.260
on WNYC Studios'
"More Perfect," which

00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:46.280
was a "Radiolab" spinoff
about the Supreme Court.

00:00:46.280 --> 00:00:49.820
His work has also appeared on
"Marketplace," "Studio 360,"

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:52.060
and "The Codebreaker" podcast.

00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:57.020
He is the recipient of a 2015
STEM Story Grant from PRX,

00:00:57.020 --> 00:01:00.950
and was a New Voices scholar at
the 2014 Third Coast Festival

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:02.360
Conference.

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:05.480
Tobin was once a professional
cellist and attended a circus

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:07.567
camp as a child, fun fact.

00:01:07.567 --> 00:01:08.400
TOBIN LOW: All true.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:10.350
KATHY TU: All true.

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:12.530
SPEAKER 1: Kathy heads
up "Nancy's" West

00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:16.100
Coast operations, AKA
her home in Los Angeles.

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:18.260
Prior to "Nancy," Kathy
did production work

00:01:18.260 --> 00:01:21.890
for a number of podcasts,
including "The Memory Palace,"

00:01:21.890 --> 00:01:24.800
"The Mortified Podcast,"
and "Masterpiece Studio."

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:27.620
And she would like it to be
noted that this whole hosting

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:29.480
thing makes her
very uncomfortable,

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:31.284
but she's leaning the F in.

00:01:34.206 --> 00:01:36.006
So thank you so much for coming.

00:01:36.006 --> 00:01:37.380
Thank you so much
for being here.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:38.421
This is really wonderful.

00:01:38.421 --> 00:01:40.800
I know we have some fans of
the podcast in the audience.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:41.300
Yes?

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:42.325
[CHEERING]

00:01:42.325 --> 00:01:42.950
Yes.

00:01:42.950 --> 00:01:43.797
Great.

00:01:43.797 --> 00:01:46.130
So I'm just going to jump
right in with a few questions.

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:50.150
I'm curious what precipitated
the creation of "Nancy,"

00:01:50.150 --> 00:01:52.110
the podcast.

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:54.466
KATHY TU: Where do
you want to start?

00:01:54.466 --> 00:01:56.090
TOBIN LOW: I'm not
just pandering here.

00:01:56.090 --> 00:01:57.650
It started with a Google doc.

00:01:57.650 --> 00:01:58.486
KATHY TU: It did.

00:01:58.486 --> 00:01:59.111
TOBIN LOW: Hey!

00:01:59.111 --> 00:02:02.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:03.432
KATHY TU: That's true.

00:02:03.432 --> 00:02:05.180
SPEAKER 1: That's amazing.

00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:07.020
TOBIN LOW: So Kathy and I met--

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:09.460
I guess three years
ago at this point--

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:12.364
at a program called The
Transom Story Workshop.

00:02:12.364 --> 00:02:14.030
It's like a boot camp
for people wanting

00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:15.119
to get into Public Radio.

00:02:15.119 --> 00:02:16.160
KATHY TU: Four years ago.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:18.350
TOBIN LOW: Four years ago.

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:20.520
And we just immediately
latched on to each other.

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.430
And we're, like, we need
to work together somehow.

00:02:23.430 --> 00:02:27.380
And it came up that we loved
this sort of "This American

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:31.214
Life," "Radiolab" style
of radio storytelling.

00:02:31.214 --> 00:02:32.630
But we didn't
really see a program

00:02:32.630 --> 00:02:36.554
that was applying that to queer
stories, like to LGBT stories.

00:02:36.554 --> 00:02:37.220
KATHY TU: Right.

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:39.650
TOBIN LOW: So we were, like,
we should just make that.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:41.577
We should figure out
a way to do that.

00:02:41.577 --> 00:02:43.910
And at the time, we were just
going to do it on our own.

00:02:43.910 --> 00:02:46.480
We were going to freelance it.

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:47.590
KATHY TU: On the side.

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:48.410
TOBIN LOW: Right.

00:02:48.410 --> 00:02:52.580
And we did what we always did
when we were procrastinating

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:54.760
on a thing, which is you
start a shared Google doc,

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:55.730
and that makes you
feel like you're

00:02:55.730 --> 00:02:57.979
getting the ball rolling,
like we're being productive.

00:02:57.979 --> 00:02:58.610
It's happening.

00:02:58.610 --> 00:02:59.985
KATHY TU: Let's
write some words.

00:02:59.985 --> 00:03:00.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:01.990
TOBIN LOW: I see you updating.

00:03:01.990 --> 00:03:03.070
I'm updating.

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:05.660
The magic is happening.

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:09.500
And then it just so happened
that maybe two weeks after we

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:12.040
decided we were going
to do this on our own,

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:17.090
WNYC opened up an open
call for podcast ideas.

00:03:17.090 --> 00:03:21.500
So we ended up pitching to
them in a "Shark Tank" style.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:24.020
We had five minutes on a stage
at a journalism conference

00:03:24.020 --> 00:03:25.290
to pitch them our idea.

00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:27.980
KATHY TU: Yeah, and there was a
clock that was counting down--

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:28.270
TOBIN LOW: Right.

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:29.510
KATHY TU: --our five minutes.

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:29.720
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:30.680
KATHY TU: It was terrifying.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:32.110
I blacked out for
the whole thing.

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:33.872
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:33.872 --> 00:03:36.080
TOBIN LOW: But-- so out of
that, we ended up winning.

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:37.940
And we got a pilot with WNYC.

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:41.390
And we developed it with them
for about a year, or like,

00:03:41.390 --> 00:03:42.530
a couple months.

00:03:42.530 --> 00:03:44.420
And then we got
greenlit out of that.

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:46.190
And that is "Nancy."

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:47.750
KATHY TU: Here we are.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:50.174
SPEAKER 1: Amazing, that
sounds like an intense start

00:03:50.174 --> 00:03:50.715
to a podcast.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:56.925
So what are your goals
for the podcast overall?

00:03:56.925 --> 00:03:59.300
Do you have particular goals
in mind for putting this out

00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:00.690
into the world?

00:04:00.690 --> 00:04:03.770
KATHY TU: I feel like I always
say my goal for the podcast

00:04:03.770 --> 00:04:05.300
is for people to
feel-- especially

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:09.230
people in the LGBT community--
to feel like they're

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:10.400
connected to something.

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:11.940
They hear different voices.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:13.880
And they're not
stuck in their corner

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:16.634
of whichever part of the
community that they're in.

00:04:16.634 --> 00:04:17.300
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:17.925
KATHY TU: Yeah.

00:04:17.925 --> 00:04:22.280
TOBIN LOW: I think we talked a
lot about moments where people

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:24.860
see something or read something
where they feel really

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:27.900
seen or recognized.

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:29.780
And so in a lot of
ways, the podcast

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:31.970
has a very simple
thought behind it,

00:04:31.970 --> 00:04:35.870
which is like, as
many people as we can,

00:04:35.870 --> 00:04:38.520
if we can give them that moment,
that would be really great.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:40.820
KATHY TU: Yeah, and you
said something recently

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:42.560
about the podcast.

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:45.797
You said that you wanted it to
be the defender of queer joy.

00:04:45.797 --> 00:04:46.630
TOBIN LOW: Oh, yeah.

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:47.120
Yeah.

00:04:47.120 --> 00:04:47.745
KATHY TU: That.

00:04:47.745 --> 00:04:51.170
I think that that is kind
of what we're aiming for.

00:04:51.170 --> 00:04:54.295
SPEAKER 1: So how do you
decide which topics to cover?

00:04:54.295 --> 00:04:56.480
KATHY TU: There are so
many topics to cover.

00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:57.615
SPEAKER 1: So many topics.

00:04:57.615 --> 00:05:01.170
And you've already
covered quite a few.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:04.160
KATHY TU: It's a balancing act
of what stories get pitched

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:05.880
to us, what stories
we find interesting,

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:08.840
what stories are
happening right now,

00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:10.550
the opportunities
we have to capture

00:05:10.550 --> 00:05:14.250
somebody trying to figure out
a thing which we love to do.

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:16.690
It's a giant balancing act.

00:05:16.690 --> 00:05:17.480
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.420
I think there's a
lot of stuff that we

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:22.616
want to cover that's sort
of on this mental list

00:05:22.616 --> 00:05:23.990
that we keep going,
of, we really

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:25.970
want to cover this
and this and this.

00:05:25.970 --> 00:05:28.490
But we also made a
hard rule for ourselves

00:05:28.490 --> 00:05:30.760
that nobody on the show
would ever just be coming on

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:31.925
to define themselves.

00:05:31.925 --> 00:05:33.840
Do you know what I mean?

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:35.810
We try really hard
not to have anyone

00:05:35.810 --> 00:05:39.350
on who's just this is who I am,
and I'm defining my identity

00:05:39.350 --> 00:05:41.270
for a larger audience.

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:44.390
So a lot of times it's
waiting for the right story

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:47.360
or the right interview
that will get at things

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:48.740
in an interesting way.

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:51.107
And so sometimes that's
the bar for something

00:05:51.107 --> 00:05:51.940
getting on the show.

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:52.990
KATHY TU: Yeah.

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:55.220
SPEAKER 1: And do you feel
like that is what makes--

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:58.580
like, what do you feel
makes "Nancy" unique?

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:02.990
Because there are obviously
other LGBTQ-focused podcasts.

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:05.100
But there is clearly
a unique angle.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:07.250
What do you feel that that is?

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:12.272
KATHY TU: I think it's that we
both love narrative stories,

00:06:12.272 --> 00:06:13.730
I don't know, more
than interviews.

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:17.540
But there are times when I just
want to listen to a narrative

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:21.907
story just because I don't have
to think too much about it,

00:06:21.907 --> 00:06:22.740
if that makes sense.

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:24.300
Like, sometimes I listen
to an interview that

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:25.924
does a really deep
dive into something,

00:06:25.924 --> 00:06:28.220
and that's fascinating.

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:31.130
But that gets me a little
bit tired at the end.

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:32.930
And sometimes it's
sort of like, I

00:06:32.930 --> 00:06:34.620
don't know, watching
good television.

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:37.730
You just sort of sit and
you let them entertain you.

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:41.600
And that's what I like about
narrative-driven stories,

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.000
the fact that we can
tell a story featuring

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.310
queer people living
their lives or whatever

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:47.330
they're going through.

00:06:47.330 --> 00:06:50.690
And I can sit back and
just let it entertain me.

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:52.550
Does that make sense?

00:06:52.550 --> 00:06:54.480
Did I answer a question?

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.300
OK.

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:58.340
SPEAKER 1: But you
also aside from having

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:02.150
folks come on and talk during
your show or be interviewed,

00:07:02.150 --> 00:07:04.550
you also share a fair
number of personal stories

00:07:04.550 --> 00:07:06.630
and anecdotes on the show.

00:07:06.630 --> 00:07:08.570
What is your
process for deciding

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:11.150
how and when you share
that personal information

00:07:11.150 --> 00:07:12.590
[? to a ?] wide audience?

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:13.504
TOBIN LOW: Uh.

00:07:13.504 --> 00:07:14.420
KATHY TU: Hm.

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:17.210
TOBIN LOW: If my therapist
tells me that it's interesting--

00:07:17.210 --> 00:07:20.360
I literally just had my
therapist pitch me on a thing.

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:22.185
It was very bizarre.

00:07:22.185 --> 00:07:24.060
I was, like, I don't
want to talk about that.

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:25.560
Or like, I don't know what
to talk about on the show.

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:26.690
And she was, like,
I can think of five

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:28.046
things you should talk about.

00:07:28.046 --> 00:07:30.236
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:35.740
So when we first
started the show,

00:07:35.740 --> 00:07:37.760
and we were working
on our pilot,

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:40.010
Kathy had been sitting
on this amazing tape

00:07:40.010 --> 00:07:42.044
where she came out to her mom--

00:07:42.044 --> 00:07:42.710
KATHY TU: Again.

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:43.820
TOBIN LOW: --again.

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:46.250
And it was this
really amazing tape

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:48.230
of the experience of
coming out specifically

00:07:48.230 --> 00:07:49.370
to an immigrant mother.

00:07:49.370 --> 00:07:53.180
And how are you dealing
with both translation

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:55.610
in a literal sense,
but also in the divide

00:07:55.610 --> 00:07:59.210
of what her experience is
versus your experience?

00:07:59.210 --> 00:08:02.510
So even when we didn't
know what the show was,

00:08:02.510 --> 00:08:04.330
we knew that that
was great tape.

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:06.600
We knew that that
was a great story.

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:10.490
So I feel a lot of us
digging into personal stuff

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:15.560
has tumbled out of Kathy's first
story being really personal

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:18.370
and people really
responding to that.

00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:20.910
And so now we have cursed
ourselves forever more--

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:21.740
KATHY TU: I know.

00:08:21.740 --> 00:08:23.865
TOBIN LOW: --to be spilling
things out on the show.

00:08:23.865 --> 00:08:26.031
KATHY TU: Every time I feel
anxious about something,

00:08:26.031 --> 00:08:28.394
I feel like our boss is, like,
maybe do a story on that.

00:08:28.394 --> 00:08:29.310
And I'm, like, dammit.

00:08:29.310 --> 00:08:30.270
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:31.360
KATHY TU: Here we go.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:32.534
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:08:32.534 --> 00:08:37.100
SPEAKER 1: [INAUDIBLE]
Also you have started

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:38.825
season two, very exciting.

00:08:41.429 --> 00:08:45.154
How do you feel you shaped
season two differently from how

00:08:45.154 --> 00:08:46.070
you shaped season one?

00:08:48.744 --> 00:08:50.660
Or did you shape it
differently, or is it more

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:53.660
of a continuation of the same?

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:55.670
TOBIN LOW: I feel like
it's a continuation.

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:59.360
Because we always knew that
we had sort of, like, 12

00:08:59.360 --> 00:09:01.370
episodes in season one.

00:09:01.370 --> 00:09:03.800
And we were very
aware that you're not

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:07.810
going to get to 12 episodes
and be, like, we did it.

00:09:07.810 --> 00:09:09.480
We've covered all the stories

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:11.480
KATHY TU: All of
them have been told.

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:14.060
TOBIN LOW: So, yeah, it
feels like season two is just

00:09:14.060 --> 00:09:16.250
an opportunity to do
more of the storytelling

00:09:16.250 --> 00:09:18.200
that we wanted to do.

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:21.660
I will say the difference is
that we have an audience base,

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:23.720
and we want to start
figuring out how

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:25.820
we interact with that audience.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:28.700
And so that was the
drive behind this project

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:31.100
we're doing called Out
at Work, which is, like--

00:09:31.100 --> 00:09:32.180
SPEAKER 1: That was going
to be my next question.

00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:33.310
TOBIN LOW: Oh, cool.

00:09:33.310 --> 00:09:35.059
SPEAKER 1: Tobin's
actually a mind reader.

00:09:35.059 --> 00:09:36.460
Actually, another fun fact.

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:38.780
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:41.090
Yeah, OK, so Out at
Work is this big project

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:43.670
we're doing that
has to do with some

00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:45.980
of the big legal stuff
about what protections

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:49.130
we do and don't have as LGBT
workers in this country.

00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:51.950
But it also sort of boils
down to the everyday stories

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:56.360
of, like, are you your
coworker's token gay friend?

00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:58.040
And do they ask
you-- but we just

00:09:58.040 --> 00:10:00.110
had a guy on this
week's episode who

00:10:00.110 --> 00:10:02.840
talks about because
he's out at work,

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:04.310
everyone assumes
that he just wants

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:05.750
to talk about sex all the time.

00:10:05.750 --> 00:10:07.958
And they're coming to him
with all their sex stories.

00:10:07.958 --> 00:10:11.640
And he's, like, I just
want this to be my job.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:13.700
But you know, there's
real stories like that,

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:16.200
just interacting with coworkers
and that kind of thing.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:19.310
And I think we're really
interested in having listeners

00:10:19.310 --> 00:10:21.950
of this show share
their stories with us

00:10:21.950 --> 00:10:26.330
and sort of get into how
that's really fascinating story

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:27.815
territory for us.

00:10:27.815 --> 00:10:29.600
So yeah.

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:31.190
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, so
this is obviously

