00:20:09.194 --> 00:20:11.610
I mean, I feel like if you can
fit "The L Word" and "Harry

00:20:11.610 --> 00:20:13.860
Potter" into 20, 25
minutes, you're super human

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:16.110
and can probably fit anything
into 20 or 25 minutes.

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.060
But are there any
topics that you did not

00:20:18.060 --> 00:20:23.040
feel you could cover in
that short of a time?

00:20:23.040 --> 00:20:24.060
KATHY TU: I think so.

00:20:24.060 --> 00:20:25.920
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:28.320
I would say if there
are, we're probably

00:20:28.320 --> 00:20:31.600
still trying to
find a way to do it

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:33.872
and probably
shouldn't say anymore.

00:20:33.872 --> 00:20:34.580
KATHY TU: Oh, OK.

00:20:34.580 --> 00:20:35.746
TOBIN LOW: No, I don't know.

00:20:35.746 --> 00:20:38.670
KATHY TU: I was going to say
like things that require deep,

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:40.350
investigative journalism.

00:20:40.350 --> 00:20:42.330
I don't that we have the
capacity yet to do it,

00:20:42.330 --> 00:20:44.180
but maybe one day in the future.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:46.346
TOBIN LOW: Yeah, we're still
figuring that part out,

00:20:46.346 --> 00:20:48.020
I think.

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:55.650
SPEAKER 1: Awesome, so for
the pieces of pop culture

00:20:55.650 --> 00:21:02.220
that you dive into, do
you feel as though these

00:21:02.220 --> 00:21:05.940
require careful consideration,
the pieces of pop culture?

00:21:05.940 --> 00:21:10.370
I was looking here, we've
got "The Golden Girls."

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:13.380
Again, "Harry Potter"
comes up pretty strongly.

00:21:13.380 --> 00:21:15.420
How do you tell stories
about pop culture?

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:17.760
Because often I
think that we find

00:21:17.760 --> 00:21:22.350
that pop culture has a
particular heteronormative

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:24.000
skew.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.830
So how do you feel
you address some

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:29.130
of-- well, heteronormative
and many other normative, very

00:21:29.130 --> 00:21:30.070
normative skew.

00:21:30.070 --> 00:21:32.610
But how do you address
issues of pop culture?

00:21:32.610 --> 00:21:35.070
And do you find yourselves
conflicted in addressing

00:21:35.070 --> 00:21:36.225
some of those things?

00:21:36.225 --> 00:21:38.920
KATHY TU: I feel
conflicted all the time,

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:40.770
especially working
on these stories.

00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:44.700
Well, things like "The Golden
Girls," for pop culture

00:21:44.700 --> 00:21:49.290
stories, I think we try to find
an angle that hasn't really

00:21:49.290 --> 00:21:53.560
been seen before.

00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:56.786
Like, for "Golden Girls,"
we were looking at the--

00:21:56.786 --> 00:21:57.660
what did you call it?

00:21:57.660 --> 00:22:03.030
Like, the fandom
around it and what that

00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:05.880
meant to people who are queer,
even though the show wasn't

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:07.310
explicitly queer.

00:22:07.310 --> 00:22:11.520
And we found different
stories about how the show

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:12.750
itself had affected us.

00:22:12.750 --> 00:22:15.930
Instead of doing the
deep dive into making

00:22:15.930 --> 00:22:19.080
that show and the actors
and whether or not

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:20.910
they liked each
other, even though I

00:22:20.910 --> 00:22:22.410
know all of those stories, too.

00:22:22.410 --> 00:22:24.210
But we couldn't talk
about those stories,

00:22:24.210 --> 00:22:26.220
because they weren't relevant.

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:31.350
So yeah, I feel like we try
to find an angle that hasn't

00:22:31.350 --> 00:22:34.350
really been covered before.

00:22:34.350 --> 00:22:35.530
Do you agree?

00:22:35.530 --> 00:22:37.680
TOBIN LOW: Yeah, well,
I think there's like--

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:38.200
it's funny.

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.380
I think pop culture,
like any of the stories

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:43.140
we do, we made a very
conscious decision early

00:22:43.140 --> 00:22:45.810
on that no one on the
show would come on

00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:47.951
as a quote, unquote
expert of anything,

00:22:47.951 --> 00:22:49.950
that they would always
be coming from the angle,

00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:53.280
like, this is my personal
relationship to this thing.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:56.370
So I think when we were
developing "The Golden Girls"

00:22:56.370 --> 00:22:58.855
episode or "The L
Word" episode, there

00:22:58.855 --> 00:23:01.230
were moments where those
stories took the shape of, like,

00:23:01.230 --> 00:23:06.270
here is a high level look
at what this show meant.

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:08.280
And then that felt
like kind of what

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:11.020
you were saying, like it
was trying to do too much.

00:23:11.020 --> 00:23:13.260
And so when we buried
down, and it was, like,

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:15.270
oh, this episode is
actually more about

00:23:15.270 --> 00:23:17.520
what people do with
fandom, or what

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:21.000
people do with something
that's not explicitly queer,

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:22.560
but they reinvent
it for themselves

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:24.180
or see it through
a different angle

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:27.310
and find that representation.

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:29.660
Like, that's the moment where
the pop culture episodes

00:23:29.660 --> 00:23:33.810
sort of click for us, when it's
about something else, not just

00:23:33.810 --> 00:23:35.850
the show, if that makes sense.

00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:41.550
SPEAKER 1: Does
anybody have questions?

00:23:41.550 --> 00:23:43.290
Does anybody want
to pop up to the mic

00:23:43.290 --> 00:23:46.830
quickly and ask some
questions of your own?

00:23:46.830 --> 00:23:48.240
Yeah, go for it.

00:23:48.240 --> 00:23:51.732
AUDIENCE: Kind of in the vein
of the Out at Work project,

00:23:51.732 --> 00:23:53.940
we talked a lot about your
sort of audience response.

00:23:53.940 --> 00:23:56.400
I'd be curious what the
professional response has been,

00:23:56.400 --> 00:23:59.840
I'd say both from maybe other
podcasters and maybe folks

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:02.280
at WNYC, et cetera.

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:04.750
TOBIN LOW: Meaning, how have
they taken to the project?

00:24:04.750 --> 00:24:06.514
AUDIENCE: How have they taken--

00:24:06.514 --> 00:24:08.763
how have they've taken to
the podcast as a whole, sort

00:24:08.763 --> 00:24:13.200
of, yeah, sort of yes,
I guess, in general.

00:24:13.200 --> 00:24:15.630
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:24:15.630 --> 00:24:18.120
KATHY TU: Well, WNYC has
been super supportive.

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:22.731
And I feel like we're
very lucky to have

00:24:22.731 --> 00:24:24.480
been able to pilot
this project with them,

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:27.570
because they let us take a
while to really figure out

00:24:27.570 --> 00:24:31.110
what our sound was before we
released it into the wild.

00:24:31.110 --> 00:24:33.240
And ever since
it's been out, I've

00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:35.790
heard nothing but good
things from our coworkers.

00:24:35.790 --> 00:24:37.860
Maybe they're just being
nice, I don't know.

00:24:37.860 --> 00:24:39.693
TOBIN LOW: I mean,
public radio, admittedly,

00:24:39.693 --> 00:24:41.460
is a very crunchy space.

00:24:41.460 --> 00:24:43.650
So there is sort of
that support in there,

00:24:43.650 --> 00:24:46.020
and a genuine
curiosity for people

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:52.920
to have their own space to talk
about identity and stuff that

00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:55.080
traditionally in larger
media doesn't get talked

00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:56.610
about or covered very much.

00:24:56.610 --> 00:25:02.010
So I feel WNYC Studios has
been super supportive of us

00:25:02.010 --> 00:25:03.240
and what we're trying to do.

00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:05.580
And super supportive,
also, of the fact

00:25:05.580 --> 00:25:08.920
that we have a very specific
audience that we're targeting.

00:25:08.920 --> 00:25:11.700
We're not that interested in
my broadening this out into,

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:12.310
like--

00:25:12.310 --> 00:25:13.050
KATHY TU: Yeah.

00:25:13.050 --> 00:25:15.600
TOBIN LOW: I mean, we're not
very interested in targeting

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:18.690
this, like here's how we explain
queer culture to a larger

00:25:18.690 --> 00:25:19.680
audience.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:21.180
They were on board
with us being,

00:25:21.180 --> 00:25:25.380
like, we are really interested
in targeting specifically

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:26.940
a queer audience.

00:25:26.940 --> 00:25:29.220
And in the specificity
of that storytelling,

00:25:29.220 --> 00:25:31.530
other people will show
up, too, because they

00:25:31.530 --> 00:25:35.460
will feel they are
getting let into a world

00:25:35.460 --> 00:25:38.400
that maybe they don't know
about and are curious about.

00:25:38.400 --> 00:25:41.299
So that kind of support
has been really awesome.

00:25:41.299 --> 00:25:43.590
The other thing I'll say,
which we were just realizing,

00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:46.272
is it's kind of hard
to troll a podcast.

00:25:46.272 --> 00:25:46.980
KATHY TU: I know.

00:25:46.980 --> 00:25:52.440
TOBIN LOW: So somebody who
disagrees with your content

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:55.020
or doesn't like
queer people, let's

00:25:55.020 --> 00:25:58.570
say, to troll a podcast they
would have to actually listen,

00:25:58.570 --> 00:26:01.920
one, and then find a quote they
don't like, and then tweet us.

00:26:01.920 --> 00:26:04.650
And then-- so the times
that that has happened

00:26:04.650 --> 00:26:09.900
is lesser than people just
sort of expressing fandom.

00:26:09.900 --> 00:26:14.670
So in that sense, I think WNYC
recognizes that podcasting

00:26:14.670 --> 00:26:20.100
can be a great space for people
to really express exactly

00:26:20.100 --> 00:26:21.576
what they want to talk about.

00:26:21.576 --> 00:26:23.820
KATHY TU: Of course,
now when you say that,

00:26:23.820 --> 00:26:25.105
and the trolls will actually--

00:26:25.105 --> 00:26:26.980
TOBIN LOW: I know, I
just invited the trolls.

00:26:26.980 --> 00:26:27.960
KATHY TU: I know.

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:30.390
But if we do get
negative messages,

00:26:30.390 --> 00:26:32.280
it's always reacting
to some headline.

00:26:32.280 --> 00:26:35.052
Nobody's actually heard it.

00:26:35.052 --> 00:26:36.510
SPEAKER 1: Have
you had experiences

00:26:36.510 --> 00:26:39.126
of people, the very few
who have trolled you,

00:26:39.126 --> 00:26:40.500
actually listening
to the podcast

00:26:40.500 --> 00:26:42.090
and having their minds changed?

00:26:42.090 --> 00:26:44.465
It sounded like the people
who are trolling you had not--

00:26:44.465 --> 00:26:46.970
it was pretty clear that
they had not listened.

00:26:46.970 --> 00:26:47.511
KATHY TU: Mm.

00:26:47.511 --> 00:26:49.630
TOBIN LOW: Oh, minds changed.

00:26:49.630 --> 00:26:54.420
Well, I will say we got an email
very early on that the person

00:26:54.420 --> 00:26:58.080
just sort of declared up top,
I'm a 55-year-old white cis

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:01.590
male, and I love your show.

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:06.510
And it helps me learn
about x, y, and z.

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:09.270
And our reaction was kind of
like, we were not expecting

00:27:09.270 --> 00:27:10.770
you, sir, but welcome.

00:27:10.770 --> 00:27:11.705
KATHY TU: Welcome.

00:27:11.705 --> 00:27:16.200
Yeah, yeah, we get
a few of those.

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:17.334
SPEAKER 1: Got one more.

00:27:17.334 --> 00:27:18.750
AUDIENCE: Apologies
if you already

00:27:18.750 --> 00:27:20.890
answered this at the very
beginning of the talk.

00:27:20.890 --> 00:27:23.790
But just wondering, how did you
guys decide on the name "Nancy"

00:27:23.790 --> 00:27:24.767
for the podcast?

00:27:24.767 --> 00:27:26.100
TOBIN LOW: Oh, good, good story.

00:27:26.100 --> 00:27:27.310
KATHY TU: Pure frustration.

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:29.745
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:29.745 --> 00:27:32.760
We originally pitched
the idea as "Gaydio,"

00:27:32.760 --> 00:27:35.940
and then decided that-- well,
number one, it was taken.

00:27:35.940 --> 00:27:42.360
But also we wanted our title to
be a little bit more inclusive

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:44.360
on the surface.

00:27:44.360 --> 00:27:46.140
If it was just
"Gaydio," I think,

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:49.500
we didn't want to
alienate anybody that

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:52.110
doesn't respond to just gay.

00:27:52.110 --> 00:27:55.680
So then we went through a
bunch of different puns, all

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:57.360
the queer puns.

00:27:57.360 --> 00:27:58.807
None of them were right.

00:27:58.807 --> 00:28:00.390
And then Tobin one
day was like, we're

00:28:00.390 --> 00:28:01.930
just going to name
it after a person.

00:28:01.930 --> 00:28:02.640
TOBIN LOW: Right.

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:05.610
There was a moment
where for a second

00:28:05.610 --> 00:28:08.445
it seemed like a good idea to
name the show "Gay Ponies."

00:28:08.445 --> 00:28:09.070
KATHY TU: Yeah.

00:28:09.070 --> 00:28:09.200
That was great.

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:10.710
TOBIN LOW: And so we walked
around for a day being,

00:28:10.710 --> 00:28:11.793
like, "Gay Ponies," right?

00:28:11.793 --> 00:28:12.510
This is good?

00:28:12.510 --> 00:28:13.420
Yes?

00:28:13.420 --> 00:28:13.920
No?

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:14.830
OK.

00:28:14.830 --> 00:28:16.459
And then we were, like--

00:28:16.459 --> 00:28:18.750
and then truly in a moment
of frustration, I was, like,

00:28:18.750 --> 00:28:20.083
let's just give it a human name.

00:28:20.083 --> 00:28:25.620
And then we landed on
this idea that "Nancy" has

00:28:25.620 --> 00:28:27.680
like a nod to queer culture.

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:31.230
It has this history as being a
term, like, a very old school

00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:34.500
term for a gay man.

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:37.070
So we liked that it had this
almost like, friend of Dorothy

00:28:37.070 --> 00:28:37.570
nod.

00:28:37.570 --> 00:28:39.340
Like, if you know, you
know kind of thing.

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:42.000
And then we also liked that
there was a bit of reclaiming,

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:43.780
because I think Nancy,
historically, has

00:28:43.780 --> 00:28:45.184
been sort of a negative term.

00:28:45.184 --> 00:28:46.600
And so we liked
that we were going

00:28:46.600 --> 00:28:49.660
to take it, and reclaim it,
and define it as something

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:51.580
new and fun and joyous.

00:28:51.580 --> 00:28:53.209
So like-- and then
there was just

00:28:53.209 --> 00:28:55.000
something irreverent
about naming a fucking

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:56.271
show after a person.

00:28:56.271 --> 00:28:56.770
You know?

00:28:56.770 --> 00:28:59.650
Like, Nancy, it was
kind of ridiculous.

00:28:59.650 --> 00:29:02.490
So it ticked a lot of boxes for
us, and we thought it was fun.

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:04.990
KATHY TU: I'm not going to lie,
I wasn't on board initially,

00:29:04.990 --> 00:29:05.820
but I trusted you.

00:29:05.820 --> 00:29:06.815
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:06.815 --> 00:29:07.600
I trusted you.

00:29:10.375 --> 00:29:11.256
Jenny's fine.

00:29:11.256 --> 00:29:13.130
AUDIENCE: So we touched
on this a little bit.

00:29:13.130 --> 00:29:14.200
And I think one of
the things I really

00:29:14.200 --> 00:29:15.640
appreciate about the
podcast, and what

00:29:15.640 --> 00:29:17.920
sets it apart from something
like "This American Life"

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:21.610
is the personal disclosure
piece and a lot of the things

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:25.000
that you've unpacked
for the world to hear.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.050
Where would you say
you've experienced

00:29:27.050 --> 00:29:31.390
the most personal growth as a
result of that since the time

00:29:31.390 --> 00:29:32.060
you started?

00:29:32.060 --> 00:29:32.740
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:33.670
KATHY TU: Well, I
feel like that's

00:29:33.670 --> 00:29:35.140
directed at me,
because I figured

00:29:35.140 --> 00:29:36.930
a lot of stuff out via podcast.

00:29:36.930 --> 00:29:38.522
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:38.522 --> 00:29:39.730
AUDIENCE: Well, both of you--

00:29:39.730 --> 00:29:42.804
I just listened to the pool
party, bathing suit episode.

00:29:42.804 --> 00:29:43.554
So there's a lot--

00:29:43.554 --> 00:29:46.390
KATHY TU: Yeah,
there's a lot of stuff.

00:29:46.390 --> 00:29:48.850
I didn't really engage
with queer media

00:29:48.850 --> 00:29:50.140
before this podcast started.

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:52.320
And as soon as Tobin and
I started working on this,

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:54.520
I was, like, oh my
god, I'm so behind.

00:29:54.520 --> 00:29:56.500
And I did a deep dive into it.

00:29:56.500 --> 00:30:00.520
But along the way, I feel
like through the podcast,

00:30:00.520 --> 00:30:04.420
I would say, I'm coming
into who I think--

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:06.880
how I identify, and how I'm
presenting to the world.

00:30:06.880 --> 00:30:09.352
And that's been
super beneficial.

00:30:09.352 --> 00:30:10.810
I was driving with
Tobin in LA when

00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:12.220
we were on vacation together.

00:30:12.220 --> 00:30:17.470
[LAUGHS] And I told him
that I don't think I

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:20.740
would be where I am now had
this project not come to be.

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:22.900
Because I've worked
through a lot of stuff,

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:27.010
like coming out to my
mom, cutting my hair,

00:30:27.010 --> 00:30:30.070
being OK with the
fact that I feel

00:30:30.070 --> 00:30:33.370
a stigma towards a certain
word that I now don't really

00:30:33.370 --> 00:30:34.090
anymore.

00:30:34.090 --> 00:30:36.850
It's been like a
big step for me.

00:30:36.850 --> 00:30:39.340
And then going to
an all queer space

00:30:39.340 --> 00:30:41.170
that originally
I was very scared

00:30:41.170 --> 00:30:43.460
to be in, because there's
too many queer people.

00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:45.310
How do I even negotiate that?

00:30:45.310 --> 00:30:46.090
And now I love it.

00:30:46.090 --> 00:30:49.190
I'm going back [INAUDIBLE]
camp next year.

00:30:49.190 --> 00:30:50.590
So it's been a huge--

00:30:50.590 --> 00:30:51.940
do you feel like I'm growing?

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:52.440
Do you--

00:30:52.440 --> 00:30:52.760
TOBIN LOW: Oh, yeah.

00:30:52.760 --> 00:30:53.301
KATHY TU: OK.

00:30:53.301 --> 00:30:54.586
TOBIN LOW: Every single day.

00:30:54.586 --> 00:30:56.710
KATHY TU: He does learn a
thing about me every day.

00:30:56.710 --> 00:30:57.376
TOBIN LOW: Yeah.

00:30:57.376 --> 00:30:59.590
KATHY TU: [LAUGHS]
So yeah, that's

00:30:59.590 --> 00:31:01.540
what the podcast
has done for me.

