00:35:29.934 --> 00:35:30.908
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:30.908 --> 00:35:33.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:33.350 --> 00:35:35.880
TOBIN LOW: Yeah, so I
started as a cellist

00:35:35.880 --> 00:35:38.587
and did that for a
long time and then

00:35:38.587 --> 00:35:41.170
had the thing that I think a lot
of our musician friends have,

00:35:41.170 --> 00:35:43.020
which is that the
training is very

00:35:43.020 --> 00:35:48.250
different than the actual life,
the living of being a musician.

00:35:48.250 --> 00:35:52.020
And so at a certain point,
I had been gigging and doing

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:54.630
orchestra gigs and
that kind of thing

00:35:54.630 --> 00:35:58.312
and just sort of had
enough awareness to be,

00:35:58.312 --> 00:36:00.270
like, I don't think this
is going to sustain me

00:36:00.270 --> 00:36:03.280
for the rest of my life.

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:05.580
And then the cool
thing about radio

00:36:05.580 --> 00:36:07.770
is it's kind of an
island of lost toys,

00:36:07.770 --> 00:36:10.260
like, there's a lot of people
who started in one thing

00:36:10.260 --> 00:36:14.610
and sort of found
their way into radio.

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:17.970
And I think what made
the transition easier

00:36:17.970 --> 00:36:21.360
for me is that I feel
like radio exercises

00:36:21.360 --> 00:36:24.840
a lot of the parts of my brain
that I used as a cellist.

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:28.020
So you're not just
telling somebody's story,

00:36:28.020 --> 00:36:31.260
but you are telling
it almost musically.

00:36:31.260 --> 00:36:33.900
You have to have a sense
of pacing and dynamics

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:39.610
and sometimes literally
working with music.

00:36:39.610 --> 00:36:43.940
And so radio kind
of felt like a--

00:36:43.940 --> 00:36:47.520
it felt somehow like
a related jump-ish,

00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:50.440
to feed this intellectual
part of myself

00:36:50.440 --> 00:36:54.100
that I wanted to take advantage
of and then also still use

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:55.930
the musical part of my brain.

00:36:55.930 --> 00:36:58.270
That being said,
I was very aware

00:36:58.270 --> 00:37:00.700
that I was jumping
from a niche thing

00:37:00.700 --> 00:37:02.200
that I probably
wasn't going to make

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:05.110
much money in to
another niche thing

00:37:05.110 --> 00:37:07.886
that I probably wasn't
going to make much money in.

00:37:07.886 --> 00:37:09.760
So there was a moment--
there were definitely

00:37:09.760 --> 00:37:12.093
moments in there where I was
like, this is the stupidest

00:37:12.093 --> 00:37:14.020
fucking thing I've ever done.

00:37:14.020 --> 00:37:15.070
But it worked out OK.

00:37:15.070 --> 00:37:16.395
But Kathy also--

00:37:16.395 --> 00:37:17.270
KATHY TU: Same thing.

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:19.390
I was in another career,
