00:37:19.390 --> 00:37:21.695
and then we became friends.

00:37:21.695 --> 00:37:23.320
SPEAKER 1: Are you
OK with sharing what

00:37:23.320 --> 00:37:24.330
that career was before you--

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:26.330
KATHY TU: Oh yeah, I went to law
school, and then I graduated.

00:37:26.330 --> 00:37:28.663
And then I was, like, don't
really want to practice law.

00:37:28.663 --> 00:37:30.640
And I decided to go
to Transom, the boot

00:37:30.640 --> 00:37:33.440
camp where Tobin and I met.

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:36.160
But it's sort of similar
in that I've always enjoyed

00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:37.300
detailed things.

00:37:37.300 --> 00:37:40.000
And so law was great for that.

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:41.980
And now, the way Tobin
and I work together--

00:37:41.980 --> 00:37:44.080
he's such a big picture
guy, about structure

00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:46.930
and how a story
should fit together.

00:37:46.930 --> 00:37:50.260
And I'm more about the
intimate details of when

00:37:50.260 --> 00:37:51.720
a piece of music should start.

00:37:51.720 --> 00:37:53.680
Should it move over
just a microsecond?

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:58.780
Or whether this cut
works because it doesn't

00:37:58.780 --> 00:38:01.180
sound natural to my ear?

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:04.150
And we tend to-- we fit
together, like a puzzle piece.

00:38:04.150 --> 00:38:06.552
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:06.552 --> 00:38:07.510
SPEAKER 1: I'm curious.

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:09.970
For a lot of us
