are sort of exploring

00:38:18.130 --> 00:38:22.420
what it's like to be out
in one way or another

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:23.450
in the workplace.

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:26.269
And I think that we're
very lucky in many ways

00:38:26.269 --> 00:38:28.060
here at Google in
comparison, particularly,

00:38:28.060 --> 00:38:31.660
to some of the places that I've
been where I was really not

00:38:31.660 --> 00:38:33.790
able to be out, that
we have a pretty

00:38:33.790 --> 00:38:37.760
supportive company and a
supportive community here.

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:39.760
I'm interested to
know if you came

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:42.160
into any personal
conflicts or challenges

00:38:42.160 --> 00:38:44.170
with moving into
the space of being

00:38:44.170 --> 00:38:47.170
sort of professionally out.

00:38:47.170 --> 00:38:50.470
Was that scary?

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:52.840
Were you worried about
putting yourselves

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:57.040
into this sort of semi or very
public space and any backlash

00:38:57.040 --> 00:38:58.409
that you might get?

00:38:58.409 --> 00:39:00.200
KATHY TU: I mean, I
was nervous about being

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:01.340
a semi-public person.

00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:04.970
But that's just a
personal anxiety thing.

00:39:04.970 --> 00:39:05.990
I'm a privacy nut.

00:39:05.990 --> 00:39:07.880
So that was weird.

00:39:07.880 --> 00:39:08.930
Did you have any?

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:10.721
TOBIN LOW: Yeah, well,
I think one thing we

00:39:10.721 --> 00:39:14.020
both talked about is that we--

00:39:14.020 --> 00:39:17.740
I don't think we ever wanted to
go into this suddenly becoming

00:39:17.740 --> 00:39:20.250
like the voice of the gays.

00:39:20.250 --> 00:39:21.250
Do you know what I mean?

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:23.160
Or like, the queer voice.

00:39:23.160 --> 00:39:27.360
So I think there was a
moment where we were, like,

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:30.340
if we do this show, and we
don't do it the right way,

00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:33.430
it's going to come off as if
we think we know everything,

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:37.520
or like as if anyone who's on
the show is an expert somehow.

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:40.300
And I think one of
the blessings of being

00:39:40.300 --> 00:39:44.350
able to do stories is
that from the jump,

00:39:44.350 --> 00:39:46.960
you're starting from
this is this person's

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:48.010
personal experience.

00:39:48.010 --> 00:39:50.470
They are speaking
from what they know

00:39:50.470 --> 00:39:52.907
and sort of telling
their piece of it.

00:39:52.907 --> 00:39:55.240
And so once we sort of figured
out-- like, oh, as hosts,

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:56.830
we can do that also.

00:39:56.830 --> 00:39:58.714
We can say we don't
know all the answers.

00:39:58.714 --> 00:40:00.130
Part of this show
is, like, trying

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:02.290
to figure out some
answers, or figure out

00:40:02.290 --> 00:40:05.110
a piece of an answer.

00:40:05.110 --> 00:40:06.000
I think that was an--

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:09.730
but there was a lot of fear
at the beginning of ever being

00:40:09.730 --> 00:40:13.480
booked on a, like, CNN
new show as a talking head

00:40:13.480 --> 00:40:15.550
and, like, this
queer thing happened.

00:40:15.550 --> 00:40:16.920
What do the queers think?

00:40:16.920 --> 00:40:17.740
KATHY TU: Thoughts?

00:40:17.740 --> 00:40:20.830
